MINORITY VIEWS
H. Res. 114 directs the Department of Homeland Security (DHS)
to provide the Committee on Homeland Security any information
in its possession related to the security implications of halting dis-
bursement of DHS grant funds. In January, the President barred
departments and agencies from awarding congressionally author-
ized and funded Federal grants, creating chaos throughout the Fed-
eral Government and among grantees. As directed by Congress,
DHS administers a range of grants—including for disaster re-
sponse, terrorism prevention, and first responders—primarily to
State and local governments. Given the important role DHS grants
play in the security and resilience of communities across the coun-
try, it is critical that the Committee understand whether and what
analysis DHS performed regarding how freezing grant funds would
affect national preparedness, disaster response, and first respond-
ers prior to implementing the President’s grant freeze.
One of the most chaotic days of the second Trump presidency
was January 27, when the White House issued a careless and slop-
py memo telling Federal agencies to stop providing Federal grant
funding to State and local governments across the country. The
memo was so bad that courts had to intervene to prevent it from
taking effect, and after publicly defending it, the White House re-
scinded the memo.1
Even with court intervention and the White House attempting to
rescind the memo, there are still reports that Federal grants are
being withheld from our communities.
H. Res. 114 demands transparency on the impact of blocking crit-
ical DHS grants, which directly threatens national security by cut-
ting vital funding for first responders, disaster recovery, and com-
munity safety programs—creating chaos and undermining our pre-
paredness. For example, DHS’s Transit Security Grant Program is
the primary means through which the Federal Government pro-
vides security support to mass transit, passenger rail, ferries, and
bus systems. Trump’s attempted grants freeze—combined with his
tearing down of key transportation advisory committees and firing
of TSA and FAA employees—puts our transportation systems at
greater risk, even as we experience a shocking increase in trans-
portation accidents.
This Committee needs to know who from DHS thought it was a
good idea to jeopardize this funding and their rationale and re-
search, if any, on the implications of doing so. Because right now,
none of that has been shared with the Committee or the public.
Donald Trump’s decision to block congressionally authorized Fed-
eral grants has halted crucial funding for programs like the Urban
